ting $2.7m with an expected useful economic life of 50 years and no resale value. The forecast return on the initial investment is 15% per year before depreciation, and the division's cost of capital is 7%. The expected annual residual income of the initial investment is calculated to be $162,000.\"", "\"ASSESSING DIVISIONAL PERFORMANCE AND INVESTMENT DECISIONS AT A MANUFACTURING COMPANY\":\"The Biscuits division (Division B) and the Cakes division (Division C) of a large manufacturing company are evaluated based on their ROI and residual income. Senior management has decided to recharge head office costs to the divisions, affecting their net profit and ROI calculations. The case involves calculating the expected annualized ROI and residual income for each division, discussing their performance, and considering the impact of a new machinery investment on Division B's ROI and residual income.\"", "\"HEAD OFFICE COSTS\":\"Head office costs refer to the expenses incurred by the central administrative functions of a company. These costs are often recharged to individual divisions or departments to reflect their share of the overall administrative burden.\"", "\"COST OF CAPITAL\":\"Cost of capital\" is the rate of return required by a company to justify an investment. It represents the opportunity cost of using capital resources for a specific purpose. Additionally, it serves as the rate of return required to make a capital investment project worthwhile and is often used as a benchmark for evaluating investment decisions.", "\"PERFORMANCE OF DIVISIONS B AND C\":\"The performance of Divisions B and C is evaluated using ROI and residual income. Both divisions have improved their performance when uncontrollable head office costs are excluded from the ROI calculation.\"", "\"DIVISION B ROI WITH INVESTMENT\":\"ROI with investment for Division B = (Annualised Net Profit / Operating Net Assets after investment) * 100. This formula is used to assess the impact of new investments on the division's profitability.\"", "\"DIVISION B RI WITH INVESTMENT\":\"RI with investment for Division B = Net Profit with investment - Imputed Interest. This formula helps determine whether the investment increases the residual income, aligning with the goal of maximizing shareholder wealth.\"", "\"BEHAVIOURAL PROBLEMS DUE TO ROI TARGETS\":\"The inclusion of uncontrollable head office costs in ROI calculations can demotivate staff, leading to frustration, reduced productivity, and potential opposition to the new system. Revising ROI targets is necessary to maintain staff motivation and performance.\"", "\"EVALUATING DIVISIONAL PERFORMANCE AND INVESTMENT DECISIONS AT CARDALE INDUSTRIAL METAL CO\":\"Cardale Industrial Metal Co (CIM Co) evaluates the performance of its divisions, Division F and Division N, using ROI and residual income. Each division operates as an investment center with full control over its assets and liabilities. The case highlights the importance of fair performance metrics and the impact of uncontrollable costs on staff motivation.\"", "\"NON-CURRENT ASSETS\":\"Non-current assets are long-term investments or assets that are not expected to be converted into cash within a year, such as property, plant, and equipment.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}